"There has been a big bang in digital file sharing, largely generated by social media sites such as Facebook and file-sharing sites such as Dropbox. Consumers have discovered new and easy ways of collaborating socially and sharing the millions of photographs and videos they take at the weekend. Now that people routinely share files between each other at home and on their mobiles, they will not be stopped when the same luxury is not extended to them in the workplace. By ignoring the sharing that is going on underneath the noses of IT departments, the enterprise is opening itself up to criminal activity, insider threats, huge data breaches and the inevitability of even more mistakes being made. The enterprise has to address that quickly. There has been a big bang in digital file sharing, largely generated by social media sites such as Facebook and file-sharing sites such as Dropbox. Now that people routinely share files between each other at home and on their mobiles, they want the same luxury in the workplace. By ignoring the sharing that is going on underneath the noses of IT departments, the enterprise is opening itself up to criminal activity, insider threats, huge data breaches and the inevitability of even more mistakes being made. Organisations need a strategy for secure sharing, and David Gibson of Varonis Systems believes he has one – and a warning for those who have allowed secure collaboration to drift."
